ristian fold as Christianity spread across Europe. Indeed, the Church proved surprisingly open to these influences, absorbing new images of death and afterlife in unpredictable fashion. Over time, however, the persistence of regional cultures and beliefs would be counterbalanced by the effects of an increasingly centralized Church hierarchy. Through it all, one thing remained constant: the deep desire in medieval people to bring together the living and the dead into a single community enduring across the generations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 4aChristianity. 4aMedieval & Renaissance Studies. 4aReligious Studies.  ahistory of christian doctrines, history of doctrine.  ahistory of religion, Paganism, Supernatural, death in popular culture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311066587140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170347840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703478/original  a978-3-11-066587-1  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles